      "description": "The Bill of Rights (BoR) is a scaffold with all six articles marked '[To be defined by human principal]'. This means the human principal has not yet defined the scope of enterprise, prohibited activities, core identity, human authority reservation, amendment protocol, or interpretation rules. Because the Mission Statement Protocol (MSP) is strictly subordinate to the BoR and translates it into machine-actionable constraints, the absence of BoR content leaves Nomos (#200) without substantive compliance gates. The current default-permissive MSP seed can authorize any action, as no BoR boundaries exist to trigger a PEM or block an Action Proposal. This effectively suspends the entire two-gate adjudication framework, operating in a faithless mode where the Arbiter (#190) verifies an empty document.",
      "grounded_in": {
        "document": "Bill of Rights",
        "sections": [
          "Article I – Scope of Enterprise",
          "Article II – Prohibited Activities",
          "Article III – Core Identity",
          "Article IV – Human Authority Reservation",
          "Article V – Amendment Protocol",
          "Article VI – Interpretation Rules"
        ]
      },
      "supporting_msp_sections": [
        "Purpose (paras 1‑2) – MSP translates BoR into objectives/invariants; with BoR undefined, MSP evaluation is vacuous",
        "Relationship to the Bill of Rights – MSP is strictly subordinate; any conflict is void, but here no BoR standard exists",
        "Amendment Protocol – PEMs for BoR conflicts cannot be generated, so no legislative feedback loop can form"
      ],
      "criticality": "critical",
      "urgency": "immediate",
      "impact": "Total absence of human-defined operational boundaries. While the MSP seed contains no rules, the procedural dependency on BoR means the entire compliance architecture is hollow; the DIO can execute any Action Proposal without a BoR scope gate. This exposes the enterprise to unlawful, safety‑critical, or values‑violating actions with no prior restraint beyond the MSP’s empty ruleset.",
      "priority": 1
    }
  ]
}

